      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was driven by a cascading failure of ritual-political legitimacy, where the inability of palatial elites to perform key religious ceremonies during a prolonged drought severed the ideological bonds holding redistributive economies together\", \"mechanism\": \"Palatial authority depended on demonstrated divine favour through successful harvest-festivals and weather-rites; repeated crop failures exposed ritual inefficacy, causing subject communities to withhold corvée labour and tribute, fragmenting the economic base from below while inter-polity alliances dissolved as each ruler's charisma failed independently\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\", \"Cyprus\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mesopotamia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Temple and palace archives show uninterrupted ritual offerings and no shift in dedicatory formulas during the period\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Evidence of drought is absent from regional pollen, speleothem, and sediment cores for the relevant decades\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian records describe the same drought but show no parallel crisis of royal legitimacy, despite a similar divine-kingship ideology\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}]}"
