      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was an epidemiological phenomenon: a multi-host pathogen exploited the dense maritime connectivity of the Late Bronze Age to become a pan-regional pandemic, collapsing populations and severing trade networks through demographic decimation rather than economic interdependence\", \"mechanism\": \"The Uluburun and Gelidonya shipwrecks are reinterpreted as vectors of a rodent-borne haemorrhagic fever; port cities like Ugarit, Tyre, and Pylos functioned as amplification nodes where co-habitation of humans, livestock, and grain stores enabled zoonotic spillover, with mortality rates exceeding 60% in densely populated coastal emporia, while inland agrarian settlements suffered secondary waves via refugee displacement\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\", \"Cyprus\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mesopotamia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Bioarchaeological analysis of burial remains shows no mass graves or mortality spikes inconsistent with normal attrition\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian medical papyri from the period describe no novel disease or unusual epidemic mortality\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Written correspondence from Ugarit and Hattusa discusses military threats and grain shortages but never mentions disease\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}]}"
