      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was a consequence of a military revolution in infantry tactics that enabled peripheral semi-nomadic groups to overwhelm chariot-based palatial armies, severing trade routes through direct conquest rather than economic contagion\", \"mechanism\": \"The adoption of the javelin-and-sword 'Naue II' warrior panoply by Aegean and Levantine populations shifted military advantage from expensive chariot elites to mass infantry formations; groups like the Sherden and Peleset exploited this to sack palatial centres and disrupt maritime trade by seizing port cities, while Egypt repelled these same groups at the Battle of the Delta (Medinet Habu) through combined arms tactics and a centralised military command that the fragmented palatial states could not replicate\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\", \"Cyprus\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mesopotamia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Naue II swords and associated military equipment appear in Egyptian-controlled territories in the same period without evidence of successful invasion\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Destruction layers at covered sites show no evidence of military assault but rather gradual abandonment\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian records at Medinet Habu describe the Sea Peoples as already defeated elsewhere, not as a novel military threat\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}]}"
