      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was triggered by a rapid climate shift that caused systemic agricultural de-synchronisation, where interdependent regions could no longer buffer each other's harvest failures through trade, turning a routine climatic fluctuation into a catastrophic famine\", \"mechanism\": \"A southward shift of the Intertropical Convergence Zone caused simultaneous drought in Anatolia and the Aegean but flooding in the Levant; the palatial redistributive system, designed to move grain from surplus to deficit regions, collapsed when all nodes experienced shortfalls concurrently, while Egypt's reliance on Nile inundation (driven by Ethiopian monsoon patterns) meant its agricultural base remained stable and even thrived as the delta retained moisture\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\", \"Cyprus\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mesopotamia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Palaeoclimate proxies show the region experienced a wetter, not drier, period during the collapse window\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian nilometer records and grain prices indicate severe famine in Egypt contemporaneous with the regional collapse\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Administrative texts from Ugarit and Hattusa show grain shipments continuing normally until the very end\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}]}"
